What kind of damage did the 2013 floods cause in Boulder?¶

By Eric Foster-Moore¶

There was a lot of flooding in Boulder in 2013. Boulder Creek experienced the biggest floods since the Boulder Creek gauge at North 75th Street started recording river levels in 1987. I wanted to find out what kind of damage these floods caused and whether there was an unptick in construction permits following the floods. Turns out there was. I was surprised to learn, however, that the uptick was not caused by an increase in permits related to flooding or repairs but to roofing. The main result of my work is the figure below. If you read on past that, you'll see how I created it and a bunch of other cool figures that I made too.

The figure below shows a few different things. Panel 1 shows the discharge of Boulder Creek. The 2013 flood is the big spike. Panel 2 shows the number of construction permit applications over time. There was also a spike in 2013, so there seems to be some initial evidence that the flooding may have caused an increase in construction permit applications, presumably because of damage to structures that needed to be repaired.

To investigate whether this was in fact the case, I parsed the column that describes what the permit was for, looking specifically for the word 'flood.' Panel 3 plots the number of these permits over time. There is no spike in 2013. So then I did the same thing for repair permits. Again, in Panel 4, we see no uptick in repair permits. Interesting and counter-intuitive. So I dug a little deeper.

It turns out that roofing permits were the most common permit application in 2013. Panel 5 plots the number of roofing construction permits applied for over time. There is indeed a noticeable uptick in roofing permits. Roofing permit applications exhibit seasonality--applications peak in the spring and then taper off. The 2013 roofing boom started with the typical ramop up in the early part of 2013 and then, after the September 2013 floods, kept going up.

So, one hypothesis to come out of this quick analysis is that the majority of the damage caused by the 2013 flood events was actually caused by precipitation. Or, perhaps, people quickly discovered that their roofs were not as waterproof as they thought.

The rest of this document¶

In the remainder of this document, you can see exactly how I created the figure above, which involved pulling the streamflow data from the Boulder Creek gauge at North 75th Street and the construction permit data from Boulder's open data portal. I clean these datasets, do some exploratory analyses, and then plot them as separate axes in the figure you see above.

I also look at the location of residential versus non-residential construction permits and at whether the lag time between permit application and permit approval is going up or down.

Streamflow data¶

I start by looking at the streamflow data from the Boulder Creek at North 75th Street gauge, which I obtained from https://waterdata.usgs.gov/nwis/dv?format=rdb&site_no=06730200&referred_module=sw&period=&begin_date=1986-01-01&end_date=2018-01-06

In [4]:
# Convert date to datetime

streamflow['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(streamflow['datetime'])

2013 Floods¶

In the figure below, I plot the discharge of Boulder Creek at North 75th Street for the entire period of record. The 2013 floods were the biggest Boulder Creek experienced since 1987. In the lower panel, I zoom in on 2013. We can see that the floods occurred in early September. Between September 11 and September 12, Boulder Creek's discharged went from 349 cfs to 4,770 cfs.

Georeferencing the permit data¶

The permit data has addresses but not latitude/longitude coordinates. The address data file on Boulder's open data site, however, has coordinate pairs for city addresses. I join these addresses with coordinates to the construction permit data so that I can do spatial operations and make maps.

Other things I tried:¶

inside_fp = flood_permits_gdf.within(floodplain)

The within method just returns a list of false values. Bet this could be made to work though.

inside_fp = gpd.overlay(flood_permits_gdf, floodplain, how='difference')

The overlay method apparently only works with sets of polygons, not points, although I suspect that when you do a Select by location operation in Arc, it is actually doing a spatial join in the background.
